The South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) also reported a break-in at its offices in an adjacent building at Parliament over the weekend. CAPE TOWN - Parliament says it's investigating a suspected break-in at its language services offices over the weekend.Locks of cupboards were broken but it's unclear whether any equipment was stolen.National Health, Education &amp; Allied Workers Union (Nehawu) says it's concerned about the safety of its members who often work in the office until late at night.The South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) also reported a break-in at its offices in an adjacent building at Parliament over the weekend.Nehawu says its members arrived at their office on Monday morning to find that it had been vandalised.The union's parliamentary representative Sthembiso Tembe says it's still unclear what was taken because some of the staffers whose cupboards were broken into are on leave. If people can just come in and do as they like, especially after what happened at the SABC offices in the Marks Building, it makes us wonder whether our representatives are safe in Parliament. Parliamentary spokesperson Moloto Mothapo would only say that the matter had been reported and was under investigation.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)